      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The deterrence argument is fundamentally flawed because it assumes criminals are rational actors who can be stopped by fear of punishment, which ignores the reality that many offenders are driven by greed, addiction, or desperation rather than a desire to break the law. While harsher penalties may reduce recidivism in some cases, they often fail to address the underlying societal issues like poverty and lack of opportunity that drive criminal behavior. Therefore, relying solely on deterrence is an incomplete strategy that ignores the complex human factors behind crime.",
